-- South African Stocks: Anglo, BHP, Aquarius, Northam, Sasol Move
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 2012-02-24T08:17:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-02-24/south-african-stocks-anglo-bhp-aquarius-northam-sasol-move.html
The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index (JALSH) 
advanced for a second day, climbed 0.5 percent to 34,280.80 by
9:58 a.m. in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active equities in the
South African market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified miner that
makes up about 9 percent of the index, gained for the first time
in three days, adding 0.7 percent to 325.90 rand. Standard &
Poor’s  GSCI Index (SPGSCI)  of commodities rose for a seventh day as
reports from  South Korea  to the U.S. and  Germany  signaled the
global economy is recovering, boosting demand for raw materials.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL)  , the world’s biggest miner, rose
0.5 percent to 252.70 rand.  Aquarius Platinum Ltd. (AQP)  , the fourth-biggest
platinum miner, slid 4.9 percent to 16.75 rand, the lowest in
more than three years. Zimbabwe rejected its plan to sell a
stake in its Mimosa Holdings Pty Ltd. joint venture with  Impala
Platinum Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  to black Zimbabweans, the company said in
a regulatory filing today.  Northam Platinum Ltd. (NHM)  , the operator of the world’s
deepest platinum mine, climbed to its highest in almost three
weeks, gaining 3.3 percent to 34 rand. Earnings more than
doubled to 198 million rand ($26 million) in the six months
through December, the company said in a regulatory filing today.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , which produces 40 percent of  South
Africa ’s motor fuel, gained 0.4 percent to 400 rand, its third
rise this week. Oil advanced a seventh day, the longest winning
streak since January 2010, on signs of economic recovery from
the U.S. to Germany and concern escalating tension with  Iran 
threatens crude supplies.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
